// =============================================================
// Rule 2 — Cross-Tool Reference in Description
// =============================================================
//
// SCHEMA AMENDMENT REFERENCES
//   - SCHEMA_NOTES.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-20: Rules classified as
//     event-time vs content/pattern.
//   - SCHEMA_NOTES.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-25: Rules 5/6 dropped;
//     final pack composition is Rules 1, 2, 3, 4.
//
// CLASSIFICATION
//   Content/pattern rule. Host-agnostic. No EventTime filter.
//   Operates on the textual content of tool descriptions at the
//   moment of ingestion, joined against a watchlist of known tool
//   names to detect descriptions that reference tools owned by a
//   different server.
//
// DETECTION PURPOSE
//   Detects MCP tool descriptions whose text references the name
//   of a tool owned by a DIFFERENT server. In a benign MCP
//   environment, a tool description describes only what its own
//   tool does. When a description names another connected tool —
//   particularly a high-privilege tool like send_email — it is
//   attempting to influence the LLM's reasoning about that other
//   tool. This is the protocol-level signature of the Tool
//   Shadowing attack class.
//
// WATCHLIST DEPENDENCY
//   This rule depends on the MCPToolNames watchlist, which
//   contains two columns:
//     - ToolName    (string) — the name of a known MCP tool
//     - ServerName  (string) — the server that owns that tool
//
//   Current contents (as of 2026-05-25):
//     ToolName       ServerName
//     send_email     send_email
//     calendar_sync  calendar_sync
//
//   The watchlist is the authoritative list of "known tools" the
//   rule treats as legitimate referents. A description matching
//   any ToolName from the watchlist is flagged as suspicious if
//   and only if the description's own ServerName differs from
//   the watchlist row's ServerName.
//
// WHY A WATCHLIST RATHER THAN SELF-JOIN OR HARDCODE
//   Three design options were considered during Phase 1:
//     - Option A: Self-join MCPProtocolLogs_CL against itself to
//       discover tool names dynamically. Pro: no external state.
//       Con: more complex KQL; risks edge cases on common
//       substrings.
//     - Option B: Watchlist (this design). Pro: explicit human
//       authority over what counts as a tool name; reusable
//       pattern aligned with SC-200 detection practices; consistent
//       with Rule 3's watchlist dependency. Con: requires
//       maintenance when new tools are added.
//     - Option C: Hardcode the two known lab tool names directly
//       in KQL. Pro: simplest. Con: reads as lab-only; not
//       generalizable.
//
//   Option B was chosen. The watchlist pattern is the production
//   standard for Sentinel detection rules requiring reference
//   data, and Rule 3 will also use a watchlist (MCPToolDescriptions
//   for hash drift). Building two watchlists demonstrates
//   competence with this Sentinel feature category.
//
// THREAT MODEL FINDING
//   - Finding 2 — The Blast Radius Problem: a malicious tool
//     description can expand its attack surface to include OTHER
//     connected tools by referencing them in its description text.
//     The MCP protocol provides no trust boundary between
//     descriptions from different servers; once both are loaded
//     into the shared LLM context window, cross-references
//     become reasoning hooks the attacker can exploit.
//
// OWASP AGENTIC TOP 10
//   ASI01 — Agent Goal Hijack
//
// MITRE ATLAS
//   AML.T0053 — LLM Plugin Compromise
//
// DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH NARRATIVE — RULE 1 + RULE 2 COVERAGE
//   Rule 1 (poisoned tool description ingested) uses keyword
//   matching against a fixed list of instruction-like patterns.
//   It catches dramatic Tool Shadowing payloads that contain
//   explicit instruction markers (IMPORTANT, you must, etc.) but
//   misses subtler payloads that achieve the same attack via
//   semantic reframing without triggering the keyword list. This
//   limitation is documented in Rule 1's header as a Finding 6
//   (Obfuscation Gap) demonstration.
//
//   Rule 2 catches a different aspect of the same attack class:
//   the structural fact that the attacker's description must
//   REFERENCE the target tool by name to manipulate the LLM into
//   redirecting calls to it. Cross-tool reference is harder to
//   obfuscate than keyword patterns — an attacker can rephrase
//   "IMPORTANT" as "essential" or "must be set to" as "should
//   route to," but cannot easily rephrase "send_email" without
//   breaking the attack mechanic.
//
//   Together, Rules 1 and 2 provide coverage across both
//   detection signatures:
//     - V1 calendar_sync (dramatic payload): caught by Rule 1
//       AND Rule 2 (high-confidence Tool Shadowing)
//     - V2 calendar_sync (subtle payload): missed by Rule 1
//       (Finding 6) but caught by Rule 2 (recovers coverage)
//
//   This is defense-in-depth at the description-ingestion layer.
//   Different attack signatures, complementary detection logic,
//   no single point of failure.
//
// LAB DATA — KNOWN POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE CASES
//   Verified against MCPProtocolLogs_CL as of 2026-05-27:
//
//   FIRES (positive):
//     calendar_sync V1 (hash 44c65aee45b061d1..., 862 chars):
//       description contains "send_email" — Rule 2 matches.
//       Expected: 18 events fire.
//     calendar_sync V2 (hash 730af110b70716da..., 606 chars):
//       description contains "send_email" — Rule 2 matches.
//       Expected: 6 events fire.
//     Combined: 24 events fire across both V1 and V2 payloads.
//
//   DOES NOT FIRE (negative):
//     send_email (hash cb006818569a05e3..., 216 chars):
//       description does not contain "calendar_sync" — Rule 2
//       correctly skips. Expected: 24 events correctly do not
//       fire.
//
//   COVERAGE COMPARISON TO RULE 1:
//     - Rule 1 precision: 100% (18 of 18 firings are V1 attacks).
//     - Rule 1 recall against calendar_sync attacks: 75% (18 of
//       24; V2 missed per Finding 6).
//     - Rule 2 precision: 100% (24 of 24 firings are real
//       cross-tool references).
//     - Rule 2 recall against calendar_sync attacks: 100% (24 of
//       24; both V1 and V2 caught).
//
//   Rule 2 closes the V2 gap that Rule 1 left open. This is the
//   defense-in-depth claim made concrete with numbers.
//
// SCOPE FILTERS
//   - EventType == "ToolDescriptionLoaded": only inspect
//     description-load events.
//   - isnotempty(ToolDescription): defensive guard against null
//     or empty descriptions.
//   - ServerName != ServerName1: exclude self-references — a
//     description naturally references its own server's tools;
//     only cross-server references are suspicious.
//   - No HostApp filter. Rule 2 is host-agnostic per
//     content/pattern classification.
//   - No EventTime filter. Same reasoning as Rule 1 — the
//     detection signature does not depend on event timing.
//
// CROSS-JOIN MECHANIC (`extend dummy = 1`)
//   KQL does not have a dedicated CROSS JOIN operator. The
//   standard idiom for "pair every left row with every right
//   row" is to add a constant column (value 1) to both sides and
//   join on that constant. The result is a Cartesian product:
//   every event row is paired with every watchlist row. The
//   subsequent `where ToolDescription contains ToolName1` filter
//   keeps only pairings where the event's description contains
//   the watchlist's tool name. The `where ServerName !=
//   ServerName1` filter then removes self-pairings.
//
//   The column rename convention is critical: after the join,
//   left-side columns retain their original names, right-side
//   columns receive a `1` suffix. `ToolName` references the
//   event's own tool name; `ToolName1` references the watchlist
//   value. The diagnostic conducted on 2026-05-27 verified this
//   convention before writing this rule.
//
// PROJECTION
//   EventTime, SessionId, HostApp, ModelName for triage context.
//   ServerName, ToolName identify the SOURCE event (the
//   description doing the referencing).
//   ReferencedTool, ReferencedServer identify the TARGET (the
//   tool being referenced) — renamed from ToolName1, ServerName1
//   for analyst readability.
//   ToolDescription for analyst review of the full reference
//   context.
//   ToolDescriptionHash for cross-reference with Rule 3
//   (watchlist hash drift detection).
//   ToolDescriptionLength for anomaly signal.
//   IngestionAgent for forensic provenance.
//
// KNOWN LIMITATIONS
//
//   Limitation 1 — Watchlist staleness.
//     Rule 2's detection is bounded by the MCPToolNames watchlist
//     contents. If new MCP servers are added to the environment
//     but the watchlist is not updated, cross-references to those
//     new tools will not be detected. Watchlist maintenance must
//     be tied to MCP server provisioning workflows.
//
//   Limitation 2 — Substring matching imprecision.
//     The `contains` operator performs case-sensitive substring
//     match. A tool named "send_email" would substring-match
//     against any description containing "send_email_v2" or
//     "old_send_email". In this lab, no such overlapping tool
//     names exist, but production deployments should consider
//     using `has` or word-boundary regex if tool naming
//     conventions allow prefix collisions.
//
//   Limitation 3 — Self-promoting descriptions not detected.
//     A description that references its OWN tools (e.g., a tool
//     suite where one tool legitimately documents the others) is
//     excluded by the `ServerName != ServerName1` filter. If an
//     attacker controls multiple tools under one ServerName,
//     they could potentially evade Rule 2 by structuring the
//     attack within their own server's namespace. Rule 4's
//     parameter-divergence detection would still catch the
//     attack at execution time.
//
// TRIAGE STEPS
//   1. Review ToolDescription content — confirm the cross-tool
//      reference is in instruction-like context (directing
//      behavior toward another tool) rather than benign
//      reference context (e.g., documentation listing related
//      tools).
//   2. Cross-check with Rule 1 — if the description also matches
//      Rule 1's keyword regex, this is high-confidence Tool
//      Shadowing (dramatic + cross-tool reference).
//   3. Cross-check with Rule 3 — verify the
//      ToolDescriptionHash against the MCPToolDescriptions
//      watchlist of approved descriptions.
//   4. Verify the ReferencedTool's actual call history during
//      the SessionId timeframe — did the LLM actually invoke
//      the referenced tool with manipulated parameters? Rule 4
//      would detect this at execution time.
//   5. If the description is confirmed malicious, disconnect the
//      offending server and capture session evidence for
//      incident response.
//
// =============================================================

let KnownTools = _GetWatchlist("MCPToolNames");
MCPProtocolLogs_CL
| where EventType == "ToolDescriptionLoaded"
| where isnotempty(ToolDescription)
| extend dummy = 1
| join kind=inner (KnownTools | extend dummy = 1) on dummy
| where ToolDescription contains ToolName1
| where ServerName != ServerName1
| project
    EventTime,
    SessionId,
    HostApp,
    ModelName,
    ServerName,
    ToolName,
    ReferencedTool = ToolName1,
    ReferencedServer = ServerName1,
    ToolDescription,
    ToolDescriptionHash,
    ToolDescriptionLength,
    IngestionAgent
| order by EventTime desc
